title: For Trade:  PPS-43C Pistol+cash for AK folder or Browning High Power
postcontent:
I am looking to trade my PPS-43C Pistol for an AK underfolder or a Browning High Power.  I will be adding an amount of cash to each deal depending on the gun offered.  I am willing to add up to $400 depending on the deal.  

I is in like new condition, and I was the first to fire it after it was manufactured behind the iron curtain, at the start of the cold war.  It is a fantastic gun chambered in 7.62x25 Tokarev, I plan on keeping it unless I can trade it + some cash for a gun on my watch list.  If I don't run across a good trade or enough cash to buy a gun I'm looking for I will be happy to keep it. :) It has 4 33rd magazines, a TROY sling and 500rds of brass cased 7.62x25 Tokarev which sell for 50 cents per round.  If you are looking to buy it with cash, I will entertain offers, but I love this thing.  It is one of my favorite guns to shoot.

This gun has a serious history starting with the siege of Leningrad in WWII and the Red Army's need for a lighter, shorter, and easier to manufacture SMG for its special troops (Tankers, Airborne and Recon).  This was the final design, replacing the famous PPSH-41 and first saw action in Leningrad, during the siege, where it was originally designed and manufactured and became a favorite of the troops of the Soviet Arny during the march to Berlin.  It hung famously from the backs of Russian soldiers raising their flag over the Riechstag and was proven reliable again and again, in many conflicts to come.  

This particular gun was made in Poland in the early 50's, after the war and was converted to semi-automatic and imported into the U.S.as a pistol. The folding stock is fixed in the closed position, but after proper licensing can be easily converted to full functionality.

title: For Sale/Trade:  80% Jig-Less AR Lower Receiver
location: Saint Paul, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
Two black 80% lowers available.  These are pretty easy to finish, you can do it with a Dremel but a drill press is recommended.  Use a #115 Dremel bit or 3/8" or smaller end mill bit to route out the center section, then drill the hammer/trigger pin holes, the selector hole and the trigger hole to finish your receiver.

Instructions are available online along with numerous youtube videos for additional support.  If you go slow and steady it's almost impossible to not finish with a working receiver.  These are going for $65 plus $10 shipping from the manufacturer, I'd like the same or trade.

If you're looking for a winter project, consider finishing an 80% lower and learn how easy it can be to build your own custom AR.
